'''Michael Dixon''' [[OBE]], MA, [[FRCGP]]{{cn|date=March 2012}} has been chair of the [[NHS Alliance]]<ref>[http://www.nhsalliance.org/default.asp NHS Alliance]</ref> since 1998. He also chairs the [[The College of Medicine|College of Medicine]], is a visiting professor at the [[University of Westminster]]{{citation needed|date=June 2011}} and president of the Health Writers Guild.<ref>[http://www.healthwriters.com/about/committees.php Health Writers Guild]</ref>  He is a [[general practitioner]] in [[Cullompton]], Devon where he has practised since 1989.{{cn|date=March 2012}}

==Career==
Current national appointments include membership of the National Leadership Network for Health and Social Care, the National Stakeholder Forum and National Steering Group for GP Commissioning.{{cn|date=March 2012}} He is an Honorary Senior Fellow in Public Policy at HSMC [[University of Birmingham]],<ref>http://www.nhsalliance.org/michael-dixon/</ref> Honorary Senior /Lecturer in Integrated Health at the Peninsula Medical School and sits on the Steering Group of the King’s Fund Enquiry on General Practice.<ref>http://www.kingsfund.org.uk/current_projects/gp_inquiry/inquiry_panel.html</ref>

He has been active in the commissioning movement since the early 1990s, when he co-founded the Mid Devon Family Doctors Commissioning Group.{{cn|date=March 2012}}  Since then he has campaigned for the right of GPs and practices to have a role in improving local health and services and been a prime mover in developing GP commissioning models that will allow them to do so.{{Citation needed|date=January 2011}}  He sat on the National Executive of the National Association of Commissioning GPs (NACGP) - founded in 1993, was a co-writer of its document “Restoring the Vision” (1997), which was commissioned by the then Minister of Health, Alan Milburn.<ref>http://www.nhsalliance.org/about-us/history-of-nhs-alliance/</ref>  When NACGP became NHS Alliance in 1998, he was elected Chairman and has continued in this role by annual election to the present.{{Citation needed|date=January 2011}}  He is a frequent speaker and national advisor on GP commissioning{{cn|date=March 2012}} and co-author of a number of books and chapters in this area (e.g. The Locality Commissioning Handbook <ref>http://www.amazon.com/dp/1857752724</ref>(1998, Radcliffe Press) and A Practical Guide to Primary Care Groups and Trusts (2001) Radcliffe Press).<ref>http://www.radcliffe-oxford.com/Books/bookdetail.aspx?ISBN=1857754913</ref>

He is currently a director of the College of Medicine.<ref>{{cite web|title=Profile: Dr Michael Dixon|url=http://www.collegeofmedicine.eu/dr-michael-dixon|publisher=[[The College of Medicine{{!}}College of Medicine]]|accessdate=7 March 2012}}</ref> 

==Alternative medicine==
His other main field of interest is complementary medicine. Co-author of ''The Human Effect'' (Radcliffe Press 2000), he believes in “patient centred medicine” and the role of the patient in self healing.{{Citation needed|date=January 2011}}  He was the medical director of [[The Prince's Foundation for Integrated Health]], which closed in 2010 after its finance director was arrested for stealing £253,000 from the organisation.<ref>[http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23869476-three-years-jail-for-accountant-at-charles-charity-who-stole-pound-253000-to-pay-mortgage.do]</ref> Dixon is a director of the College of Medicine which opened in 2010.<ref>[http://www.collegeofmedicine.org.uk College of Medicine]</ref><ref name=BMJ_COLLEGE>{{cite news | title=Prince’s foundation metamorphoses into new College of Medicine | author=Nigel Hawkes | publisher=British Medical Journal | year=2010 | volume=341 | pages=6126 | doi=10.1136/bmj.c6126|url=http://www.bmj.com/content/341/bmj.c6126.full}}</ref> He has been criticised by professor of complementary medicine and [[alternative medicine]] campaigner [[Edzard Ernst]] for advocating the use of complementary medicine. Ernst said that the stance of the NHS Alliance on complementary medicine was "misleading to the degree of being irresponsible."<ref>[http://www.pulsetoday.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=4121964 Academics and NHS Alliance clash over complementary medicine]</ref>

==Publications==
* The Locality Commissioning Handbook (Radcliffe Press 1997),
* The Human Effect (Radcliffe Press 2000)
* A Practical Guide to Primary Care Groups and Trusts (Radcliffe Press 2000)
* Practice-based Commissioning: From good idea to effective practice 2007
* Co-author of many  NHS Alliance documents  including Restoring the Vision (1997) and Implementing the Vision (2000).  As a Fellow of Exeter University, he had written a number of research papers on complementary medicine and the therapeutic relationship.

==Personal life==
Michael Dixon is married to a professional artist, Joanna and they have three children, Finn, May and Liberty.{{Citation needed|date=January 2011}}

